  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a felony in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three steps: placement, layering, and integration.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is prosecuted under several federal statutes, including the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986, and the USA PATRIOT Act. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment. Specifically:\n\n1. **Fines**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n2. **Imprisonment**: Convictions can result in prison sentences of up to 20 years per count.\n3. **Additional Penalties**: Convicted individuals may also face forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from the illegal activity.\n\nIn addition to federal laws, many states also have their own statutes addressing money laundering, which can carry additional penalties.\n\nIt's important to note that even involvement in a single transaction can lead to serious legal consequences if it is found to be part of a money laundering scheme. Therefore, engaging in activities that could be construed as money laundering is highly illegal and subject to strict penalties.",
